Doc,<br><br>
Warriors have always been taught the power of the philosophers.  I to am a student of many.  Without this exposure you may never understand your enemy or your allies.<br><br>
I have given thought to statement.<br><br>
&quot;To a silent warrior: I have long been a student of the I ching and Sun Tsu, and both continue to teach me the wisdom of war and peace. And that changes must continue.&quot;<br><br>
I to have studied these texts.  I suggest a review of Lao Tzu &quot;Tao Te Ching&quot;.  It offers another outlook.  A philosophy of meekness as the surest path to survival.<br><br>
Know contentment<br>
And you will suffer no disgrace;<br>
Know when to stop<br>
And you will meet with no danger.<br>
You can then endure<br><br>
It is because he does not contend that no one is in a position to contend with him.<br>
It is because he does not contend that he is never at fault<br><br>
I assume you are versed in these ideas because the Taoist were avid students of I Ching.<br><br>
To follow both paths of I ching and Sun Tsu would lead to confusion.  Have you chosen yet or are you embroiled in the struggle between the two extremes.<br><br>
Before you chose try Attila the Hun and the Five Rings by Miyamoto Musashi.  Couple this with the Wisdom of Ed's forefathers and you will understand a Warrior.<br><br>
I am neither a Taoist or a follower of I Ching.  A little too mystical for me.<br><br>
I understand the game!
